8238EA67282940FA896DC6858BD7DC73.description:
Engage with representations of goods available in
the school cafeteria.

11C455DB59824036972419DD08332A55.description:
Understand that money is exchanged for goods in
stores and restaurants.

C34A3DAC2AA941558CFFAB08A0DB2005.description:
Locate prices and goods on a menu (cafeteria) or
other advertisement.

3C000B321B2244B1A0A07B845E475182.description:
Identify
the price of goods
(e.g., using menus,
ads, price tags).

4B1A2DEA6617405AB920B9C51E96A783.description:
Identify
different ways to get
price information on
the same items (e.g.,
sale ads, store signs).

0E6871CAE3AA4591A2EEA6E8F4A3122A.description:
Compare the
prices of similar
goods.

A2193511D4564B09BA20B9B2BA5923E1.description:
When selecting
items to buy, individuals can
weigh costs and benefits
and compare the price and
quality of available goods and
services.

E6B5DFBCE4324F01A3B77B54E3FA53C7.description:
Engage with representations of goods available in
the school cafeteria.

3BD6817B8D294A6189D3516BBF949E6B.description:
Match representations of goods supplied by the cafeteria
and school store (or other sources) with representations
of suppliers.

AFF0BF9FA440473AB4D3A5A215768148.description:
Identify
goods that are
readily available
in the local
environment (e.g.,
milk in cafeteria,
pencils in school
store).

53B1F72BE00B4449A94E729E6F37A004.description:
Identify
goods that are
more expensive
and discuss what
determines the cost.

24B2D238510148FD924BA8617D0C203B.description:
Explain
why some goods
are easier to find
than others and
how this affects
price.

FB99E3ADC1574212A45FC80E3C26FA46.description:
The interaction
of supply and demand,
influenced by competition,
helps to determine price in a
market. This interaction also
determines the quantities
of outputs produced
and the quantities of
productive resources (e.g.,
entrepreneurship, human
resources, natural resources,
capital) used.

696212D711DA4C78BCCC8303EF1D56F8.description:
Engage with representations of climatic regions
where farming/agriculture is favorable and not
favorable.

E6E76E6E19F843BCBC81A8562ADC591E.description:
Sort items with country of origin labels and sort into
“U.S.” and “Somewhere Else.”

96DB0C01D4354E428DFA4F0AA84BC435.description:
Identify
an item that is not
locally produced
(e.g., bananas,
pineapples).

CE3FE1CDB82F49DD9519F6DC1DA3CF86.description:
Identify
an item that is
imported and give
one reason why the
item is imported (e.g.,
bananas, pineapples).

4E9346AD92AA47D0B04513086EF9A883.description:
Compare
a locally produced
item with an
imported item and
explain why people
trade.

1263247E26BE4C8F877865F2C07B9E9C.description:
When regions and/
or countries specialize, global
trade occurs.

B3621F2EAE95445ABD5B03A308F69C13.description:
Engage with representations of people
making/ manufacturing items (e.g., assembly
line, bakery, construction site).

5E13477A068F4A4998CFC6A6371985F8.description:
Engage with products in an advertisement by
selecting items the student is interested in purchasing.

BED7F705DF7945458639F0AE64E6643B.description:
Sort items from a set into categories of consumer
(e.g., cook, student, athlete, teacher).

802CC9E887F1429A8F44F5EBBC780845.description:
Match
products to
the intended
consumer.

D217282CFED34E018E27C0B8801CC84D.description:
Identify
different methods
of production for
given goods (e.g.,
single item vs. mass
production).

962414DE2ECE41AFB222F0306D05FD2E.description:
Describe
how the wants of
people determine
what goods and
services are
produced.

EFE47061F57D48FD89E7D169077AE19F.description:
The fundamental
questions of economics
include what to produce, how
to produce, and for whom to
produce.

683EC9D365C84CCFB4E7561B4B080AB1.description: Engage with representations of different types of stores.

B2E30E84A9BD40D5A9DB27FEA8AFFD35.description:
Match items with the stores at which they can
be purchased.

35FF3D434D614CF58D8F7C166FEA7094.description:
Identify
an item that may
have a different
cost at another
store.

F853160B51B04F4983AF9DB05DB55088.description:
Use
multiple sources to
make an informed
economic decision
(e.g., advertisements,
price comparisons).

EC1BA30AB2BC4434843B89E5B57F980E.description:
Identify the
short- and
long-term
consequences of
a personal
economic
decision.

9C96B814DCA746C1947517B4E1DC90EB.description:
The choices made by
individuals and governments
have both present and future
consequences. The evaluation
of choices is relative and may
differ across individuals and
societies.

6D6A0DDC97A544B0944EA30CF50B5CCC.description: Engage with objects that can be sorted.

C95952E1803441429AB8A7E87A6DD951.description:
Create a single data point by counting the number of
items in a group.

29846D55FC3248CAACCDC99A6171C9AB.description:
Create a data set by counting and grouping items
based on given characteristics (e.g., color, size).

7B689F2343934776909E654009FF73CB.description:
Identify
what a data set is
representing.

45778DC68B0E4036BCACFFBE1FC9E593.description:
Identify a
similarity between two
sets of data.

16C94925DD4C4ECEB5384B7FC5818B52.description:
Compare
different sets of
data to draw a
conclusion.

043ADF0A58AD45AAADC4C4033D94B5AD.description:
Economists compare
data sets to draw conclusions
about relationships among
them.

51FE04ED5D4945ECA8AAA9588EB8F65E.description:
Engage with the concept of choice by selecting one item
from a given set (e.g., books, games).

E38A6FEDF40441BA96F416B6E34547E8.description:
Participate in “voting” on a class decision (e.g., which
book to read, game to play) where each student has an
equal say.

80B58474ACBD4B37942DDEE8284C06BD.description:
Understand that citizens in a democracy vote for
their leaders.

D9D5CE5ED17F4B7DADFB10A967C9FC8C.description:
Recognize
characteristics
of a democracy
(e.g., citizens
elect leaders,
citizens hold the
power in
decision-making).

2415F5964C2F4C559387808EC265F028.description:
Match
various types of
government (e.g.,
monarchy, theocracy,
dictatorship,
democracy) with their
definitions.

072973D270A146ACB49278F46A42F98D.description:
Compare
and contrast two
of the four types
of government
(e.g., monarchy,
theocracy,
dictatorship,
democracy).

BFFFA021307F42A380D47C11070008E1.description:
Governments can be
categorized as monarchies,
theocracies, dictatorships, or
democracies, but categories
may overlap and labels may
not accurately represent
how governments function.
The extent of citizens’
liberties and responsibilities
varies according to limits on
governmental authority

ABD48772972548F28DA1D8302A5F0677.description:
Build understanding of “opinion” by sharing stories
of things students enjoy.

E62D8BA7A6314C12B592D07038FBF062.description:
Share opinions, both likes and dislikes, within a
category (e.g., colors, foods, games).

5F147F307B5846399A604C229000987D.description:
Understand that opinions may differ from one person
to another.

94A9D8D7C6CC4CF49E5EC44CD5464506.description:
Provide
examples of
differences of opinion
on an issue between
individuals or within a
group.

E3885E52A8A24A939C132351C18B74F1.description:
Identify
that different
sources can
have different
perspectives on an
issue (e.g., media
sources, historical
vs. contemporary,
individual vs.
group).

1C2418B02BEE49B9B1AD540E65A57FBE.description:
Different perspectives
on a topic can be obtained
from a variety of historic
and contemporary sources
and used to effectively
communicate and defend
an evidence-based claim.
Sources should be examined
for accuracy and credibility.

4FE2EE1BD0744C9BA7A541CBAE681187.description:
Engage with images of symbols representative of
major religions in the Eastern Hemisphere.

1E8B03BBB8784691920EFD415FFEE6B7.description:
Identify or match images of symbols with
corresponding religions.

376FB73E39CE44E8BC77CF35C597CDE0.description:
Understand that people of different religions may
have different beliefs.

6BAC0C2A82F1469D9628EEFBF48A4C1D.description:
Identify
different religions
that have impacted
the Eastern
Hemisphere.

609D3E4432B849AC935C30370C029DAC.description:
Focusing
on the Eastern
Hemisphere,
identify one
characteristic
of the major world
religions.

D6261B4BC07343FB9FF3FBCEA7A81B5C.description:
Determine
one influence
or impact that
religion has had
in the Eastern
Hemisphere.

1B68EEEEB8C04449A5F83B8D05CF3F70.description:
Diffusion of
agricultural practices and
products, technologies,
cultural practices, and major
world religions (e.g.,
Buddhism, Christianity,
Hinduism, Islam and Judaism)
impacted the Eastern
Hemisphere.

081F3A4F1C6F4A68A21D3AB271145895.description:
Engage with models or representations of current forms of
transportation (e.g., cars, school buses, airplanes).

9DBD5D117E814DFE85749ECB99055D8B.description:
Sort models or representations of forms of
transportation into “today” and “long ago.”

DC1143A3A58D498ABED4C32E6034741B.description:
Identify
ways people move
from one place to
another.

841845D3737B467B8DB25441399E7590.description:
Describe
factors that cause
people to move away
from or to an area.

535CA2A10AF04C2B8308A80A4452D780.description:
Compare
and contrast the
movement in the
past and today
of products and
people from
place to place
in the Eastern
Hemisphere.

2760B2AF59F145E6BE02EEC24C3E1808.description:
In the past and today,
political, environmental,
social, and economic factors
have caused people,
products,
and ideas to move from
place to place in the Eastern
Hemisphere.

FE9EC074CDD74A56AAD287A38515DA52.description:
Actively engage with the natural environment outside
of the school.

8B8979DCD36042A5BBB2E532453D4919.description:
Identify features of the natural environment that
exists outside of the school.

61DF576502634E918F8F91B21D0FDFB7.description:
Identify examples of how human activities have
modified the environment by sorting pictures or
other representations.

B5BAF0BBDF0E41AC9EFACF42F3E39F38.description:
Identify
one way the
environment has
been disturbed due
to human activities
(e.g., pollution).

F181A4A8948C46B58F2E4947EB8E543A.description:
Explain
how human activities
have altered physical
environments
(e.g., how humans
contribute to
pollution).

37F2195A0F9546B69F01CBDFF97B2FFE.description:
Identify
both positive and
negative outcomes
of a man-made
environmental
change occurring
within the Eastern
Hemisphere.

03BB7481438049D59A789B7B5570CF76.description:
The variety of
physical environments within
the Eastern Hemisphere
influences human activities.
Likewise, human activities
modify the physical
environment.

6E3DCB0AF27E493F9E429686915C7D2B.description:
Engage with representations of the physical
environment, possibly through tactile interaction with
water, soil, sand, and rocks, and hot and cold air
temperature, to connect with the idea of different earth
surfaces.

C893FAA1C8AC4C7D8EDE8A45C35C9341.description:
Identify physical characteristics of regions using
pictures or other representations (desert, mountains,
bodies of water, forest).

190D76C8B6E6409BBEF7264FA67DEF18.description:
Identify
a physical
characteristic that
can be used to
compare regions
(e.g., landforms,
climate, population,
culture, or
economy).

C28DC3CC0B9244C8A4EFEA18CA76813F.description:
Identify
physical
characteristics of a
given region.

042A0940C43248CBB67A9A0202C501AC.description:
Compare
and contrast
the physical
and cultural
characteristics of
different regions
(e.g., forest/desert,
rural/suburban,
plains/mountains).

5BAAA82D904441E99FD1EDC134673203.description:
Regions can be
determined, classified, and
compared using various
criteria (e.g., landform,
climate, population, culture,
economy).

4772D9C9DDF24115A5F30ED5F279F172.description: Engage with a sphere as a representation of the earth.

8A8A3A9CDB0647828EF91B340935CD8B.description:
Use manipulatives or illustrations to create circles
around a sphere (e.g., put a string(s) around a styrofoam
ball, use a marker to draw circles around a ball).

CD96709AFEF6446D8C146DD4D98A6359.description:
Locate
the equator on
a globe, map,
or
geographical tool.

4200EA9EECA5439E8CAEA2181CB62D65.description:
Locate a
major feature and/
or landform on a
globe or using a
geographical tool
in relation to the
equator.

4FAA814792054A7894E50168249CB188.description:
Utilize
latitude and
longitude to locate
a major place
and/or feature
using a globe or a
geographical tool.

F196C43D81E340C09A6EFDF8B85F6575.description:
Latitude and longitude
can be used to identify
absolute location.

A838072DF64247458FF400087C6973A1.description: Engage with a representation of the school.

7CD08780CCA5442EBD07F4A6D8EF22C6.description: Recognize that a map or model represents a real place.

9731676AC9B0455EA60BEE4EEE73D0B7.description:
Identify possible uses for maps or models (e.g.,
building exits, navigation, weather forecast).

0A058F4EC2A84A6FB21A1F2480515DD9.description:
Identify the different features of maps that make
them useful for different purposes.

015CBB3295B5425F8B6673F125491A4B.description:
Identify
a specific map for
a specific
purpose.

4F48F441E85F4264A9345AF1648225DF.description:
Use
the appropriate
geographic tool to
locate a specific
place or piece of
information.

4695B92C514345B5827FC5CD65521275.description:
Use
appropriate maps,
globes and other
geographic tools
(e.g., Internet) to
locate various sites
or places.

7D465C71DCDA4EF8BBDF96759533A323.description:
Geographic tools can
be used to gather, process
and report information
about people, places, and
environments. Cartographers
decide which information
to include and how it is
displayed.

498856E698314ABE9FCECB7763B2DD7C.description:
Engage with interactive tools (blocks, Legos, drawing,
verbal description) to represent a structure built by
people.

DA8C46672BCF4F0590BE8E822356C158.description:
Create a representation of a structure in the
local community.

53525DBF904D4F54823B7FD256BFA674.description:
Recognize that people in different parts of the world
build different types of structures.

1BC073553EDB4BFFB1ED7D32777DD8C4.description:
Recognize that structures built long ago look different
than modern structures.

6437197C69834E5FA101ED3E5869EC93.description:
Match a
structure with its
specific society
(e.g., pyramid to
Egypt).

AE7EAA9CF12141DD9FFB97ACA2FE103D.description:
Identify
key features of a
specific society (e.g.,
government,
religion, agriculture).

30B1DD9A6F6246CEA3DC82A6FC2912FB.description:
Compare the key
features of
societies in
the Eastern
Hemisphere
(e.g., Egypt,
India, China,
Mesopotamia).

68BC4FE1F81549E9BED9DA2AE2C1E72E.description:
Early civilizations
(e.g., India, Egypt, China,
Mesopotamia) had unique
governments, economic
systems, social
structures, religions,
technologies, and
agricultural practices and
products. The cultural
practices and products of
these early civilizations can be
used to help understand the
Eastern Hemisphere today.

F5ABE1D7FB8F4405B7071ECD612F80E7.description:
Engage with a ruler/yardstick to understand
beginning, middle, and end.

8D4AABCC7C7D402E9EE917C4ABEDE21A.description:
Understand that events happen in order (first,
second, third) using a classroom schedule.

AF4A4AC4C29B4E0098E4CF1F29F95DCD.description:
Identify
two different
events occurring at
the same time.

F5574076EA084EFDB3B28B1BD0C06CED.description:
Arrange
events in
chronological order
on a multiple tier
timeline.

45B6A9064A5541D7AC3372D6613D0B3B.description:
Multiple tier timelines
can be used to show
relationships among events
and places.
